---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout title="Michael E. Wright, PhD — Wright Lab">
  <main class="page wide">
    <span class="section-eyebrow">Principal Investigator</span>

    <div class="pi-header">
      <div class="pi-portrait">
        <img src="/images/michael-wright-v2.jpg" alt="Michael E. Wright, PhD" />
      </div>
      <div class="pi-intro">
        <h1>Michael E. Wright, PhD</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          Associate Professor &middot; Department of Molecular
          Physiology and Biophysics
        </p>
        <p class="muted">University of Iowa &middot; Carver College of Medicine</p>
        <p>
          <a href="mailto:michael-e-wright@uiowa.edu">michael-e-wright@uiowa.edu</a> &middot;
          319-384-1764
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pi-body">
      <h2>About</h2>
      <p>
        Michael E. Wright, PhD, is an Associate Professor in the Department of Molecular
        Physiology and Biophysics at the University of Iowa
        Carver College of Medicine. He earned his PhD in Molecular and Cellular Biology from
        the University of Washington in Seattle, and completed postdoctoral training in
        quantitative mass spectrometry and systems biology at the Institute for Systems Biology
        in the laboratory of Ruedi Aebersold. He joined the University of Iowa faculty in 2008.
      </p>
      <p>
        The Wright laboratory uses quantitative mass spectrometry and proximity-labeling
        proteomics to map subcellular protein&ndash;protein interaction networks in preclinical
        models of human disease, with a particular focus on androgen receptor (AR)&ndash;driven
        diseases such as prostate cancer. The lab is interested in how signaling complexes
        coordinate cellular proliferation, cell death, and differentiation &mdash; and in
        identifying druggable receptors that can selectively trigger latent cell-death pathways
        or promote growth arrest through differentiation.
      </p>
      <p>
        Bridging classical biochemistry with modern proteomic platforms, the lab develops novel
        proximity-labeling enzymes for capturing post-translational modifications in complex
        matrices, builds reagents and methods that make protein-complex interrogation more
        reproducible, and applies these tools to mechanistic questions in disease biology.
      </p>

      <h2>Training</h2>
      <ul class="cv-list">
        <li><strong>Postdoctoral Fellow</strong> &mdash; Institute for Systems Biology, Seattle, WA. Laboratory of Ruedi Aebersold.</li>
        <li><strong>PhD, Molecular and Cellular Biology</strong> &mdash; University of Washington, Seattle, WA.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Curriculum Vitae</h2>
      <p>
        Full CV available upon request &mdash; please email
        <a href="mailto:michael-e-wright@uiowa.edu">michael-e-wright@uiowa.edu</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </main>

  <style>
    .pi-header {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: 320px 1fr;
      gap: 2.5rem;
      align-items: center;
      margin: 1.5rem 0 3rem;
    }
    .pi-portrait img {
      width: 100%;
      aspect-ratio: 3 / 4;
      object-fit: cover;
      border-radius: 8px;
      box-shadow: 0 8px 24px rgba(15, 44, 46, 0.15);
    }
    .pi-intro h1 {
      margin-top: 0;
      margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    }
    .pi-intro .lead {
      margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    }
    .pi-body {
      max-width: 760px;
    }
    .cv-list {
      list-style: none;
      padding: 0;
    }
    .cv-list li {
      padding: 0.75rem 0;
      border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    }
    .cv-list li:last-child { border-bottom: none; }

    @media (max-width: 700px) {
      .pi-header {
        grid-template-columns: 1fr;
        gap: 1.5rem;
      }
      .pi-portrait {
        max-width: 280px;
      }
    }
  </style>
</Layout>
